# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectral-analysis-stats
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In signal processing, the power spectrum $S_{xx}(f)$ of a continuous time signal $x(t)$ describes the distribution of power into frequency components f composing that signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Fourier analysis shows that any physical signal can be decomposed into a distribution of frequencies over a continuous range, where some of the power may be concentrated at discrete frequencies.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The statistical average of the energy or power of any type of signal (including noise) as analyzed in terms of its frequency content, is called its **spectral density**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] When the energy of the signal is concentrated around a finite time interval, especially if its total energy is finite, one may compute the **energy spectral density**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] More commonly used is the **power spectral density** (PSD, or simply **power spectrum**), which applies to signals existing over *all* time, or over a time period large enough (especially in relation to the duration of a measurement) that it could as well have been over an infinite time interval.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The PSD then refers to the spectral power distribution that would be found, since the total energy of such a signal over all time would generally be infinite.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Summation or integration of the spectral components yields the total power (for a physical process) or variance (in a statistical process), identical to what would be obtained by integrating $x^{2}(t)$ over the time domain, as dictated by Parseval's theorem.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The spectrum of a physical process $x(t)$ often contains essential information about the nature of x .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] For instance, the pitch and timbre of a musical instrument can be determined from a spectral analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The color of a light source is determined by the spectrum of the electromagnetic wave's electric field $E(t)$ as it oscillates at an extremely high frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Obtaining a spectrum from time series data such as these involves the Fourier transform, and generalizations based on Fourier analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] However this article concentrates on situations in which the time series is known (at least in a statistical sense) or directly measured (such as by a microphone sampled by a computer).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The power spectrum is important in statistical signal processing and in the statistical study of stochastic processes, as well as in many other branches of physics and engineering.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Typically the process is a function of time, but one can similarly discuss data in the spatial domain being decomposed in terms of spatial frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In physics, the signal might be a wave, such as an electromagnetic wave, an acoustic wave, or the vibration of a mechanism.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The *power spectral density* (PSD) of the signal describes the power density of the signal as a function of frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Power spectral density is commonly expressed in the SI unit watt per hertz (W/Hz).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] When a signal is defined in terms of only a voltage varying in time, for instance, there is no specific power associated with a given voltage.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In this case "power" is simply reckoned in terms of the square of the signal, as this would always be *proportional* to the actual power delivered by that signal into a given impedance.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] So one might use the unit V2⋅Hz−1 for the PSD.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] *Energy spectral density* (ESD) would have the unit V2⋅s⋅Hz−1, since energy is power multiplied by time (e.g., watt-hour).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In the general case, the unit of PSD will be the ratio of unit of variance per unit of frequency; so, for example, a series of displacement values (in meters) over time (in seconds) will have PSD with the unit m2/Hz.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In the analysis of random vibrations, the unit *g*02⋅Hz−1 may be used for the PSD of acceleration, where *g*0 denotes standard gravity.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Mathematically, it is not necessary to assign physical dimensions to the signal or to the independent variable.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In the following discussion the meaning of *x*(*t*) will remain unspecified, but the independent variable will be assumed to be that of time.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] A PSD can be either a *one-sided* function of only positive frequencies or a *two-sided* function of both positive and negative frequencies but with only half the amplitude.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Noise PSDs are generally one-sided in engineering and two-sided in physics.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In signal processing, the energy of a signal $x(t)$ is given by $E\triangleq \int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\left|x(t)\right|^{2}\ dt.$ Assuming the total energy is finite (i.e. $x(t)$ is a square-integrable function) allows applying Parseval's theorem (or Plancherel's theorem).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The theorem also holds true in the discrete-time cases.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The function ${\bar {S}}_{xx}(f)$ and the autocorrelation of $x(t)$ form a Fourier transform pair, a result also known as the Wiener–Khinchin theorem (see also Periodogram).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] By Ohm's law, the power delivered to the resistor at time t is equal to $V(t)^{2}/Z$ , so the total energy is found by integrating $V(t)^{2}/Z$ with respect to time over the duration of the pulse.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The value of the energy spectral density at f is then estimated to be $E(f)/\Delta f$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In this example, since the power $V(t)^{2}/Z$ has the unit V2⋅Ω−1, the energy $E(f)$ has the unit V2⋅s⋅Ω−1 = J, and hence the estimate $E(f)/\Delta f$ of the energy spectral density has the unit J⋅Hz−1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In many situations, it is common to omit the step of dividing by Z so that the energy spectral density instead has the unit V2⋅s·Hz−1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] But in the mathematical sciences the interval is often set to 1, which simplifies the results at the expense of generality.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The above definition of energy spectral density is suitable for transients (pulse-like signals) whose energy is concentrated around one time window; then the Fourier transforms of the signals generally exist.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] For continuous signals over all time, one must rather define the *power spectral density* (PSD) which exists for stationary processes; this describes how the power of a signal or time series is distributed over frequency, as in the simple example given previously.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Here, power can be the actual physical power, or more often, for convenience with abstract signals, is simply identified with the squared value of the signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] For example, statisticians study the variance of a function over time $x(t)$ (or over another independent variable), and using an analogy with electrical signals (among other physical processes), it is customary to refer to it as the *power spectrum* even when there is no physical power involved.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] If one were to create a physical voltage source which followed $x(t)$ and applied it to the terminals of a one ohm resistor, then indeed the instantaneous power dissipated in that resistor would be given by $x^{2}(t)$ watts.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] When P is non-zero, the integral must grow to infinity at least as fast as T does.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] That is the reason why we cannot use the energy of the signal, which is that diverging integral.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In analyzing the frequency content of the signal $x(t)$ , one might like to compute the ordinary Fourier transform ${\hat {x}}(f)$ ; however, for many signals of interest the ordinary Fourier transform does not formally exist.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] However, under suitable conditions, certain generalizations of the Fourier transform (e.g. the Fourier–Stieltjes transform) still adhere to Parseval's theorem.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The convolution theorem then allows regarding $|{\hat {x}}_{T}(f)|^{2}$ as the Fourier transform of the time convolution of $x_{T}^{*}(-t)$ and $x_{T}(t)$ , where * represents the complex conjugate.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In order to prove the claim below Eq.2, we will find an expression for $[{\hat {x}}_{T}(f)]^{*}$ that will be useful for the purpose.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Now, let's demonstrate the claim below eq.2 by using the demonstrated identity.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In addition, we will make the substitution $u(t)=x_{T}^{*}(-t)$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Assuming the ergodicity of $x(t)$ , the power spectral density can be found once more as the Fourier transform of the autocorrelation function $R_{xx}$ , a property known as the Wiener–Khinchin theorem.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Many authors use this relationship to define the power spectral density in terms of the autocorrelation function instead of the Fourier transform of the signal as we have done.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The power of the signal in a given frequency band $[f_{1},f_{2}]$ , where $0<f_{1}<f_{2}$ , can be calculated by integrating over frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In this case the time interval T is finite rather than approaching infinity.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] This results in decreased spectral coverage and resolution since frequencies of less than $1/T$ are not sampled, and results at frequencies which are not an integer multiple of $1/T$ are not independent.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Just as with the energy spectral density, the definition of the power spectral density can be generalized to discrete time variables $x_{n}$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] As before, the actual PSD is achieved when N (and thus T ) approaches infinity and the expected value is formally applied.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In a real-world application, one would typically average a finite-measurement PSD over many trials to obtain a more accurate estimate of the theoretical PSD of the physical process underlying the individual measurements.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] This computed PSD is sometimes called a periodogram.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] This periodogram converges to the true PSD as the number of estimates as well as the averaging time interval T approach infinity.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] If two signals both possess power spectral densities, then the cross-spectral density can similarly be calculated; as the PSD is related to the autocorrelation, so is the cross-spectral density related to the cross-correlation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Given two signals $x(t)$ and $y(t)$ , each of which possess power spectral densities $S_{xx}(f)$ and $S_{yy}(f)$ , it is possible to define a **cross power spectral density** (**CPSD**) or **cross spectral density** (**CSD**).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Note that $S_{xy}^{*}(f)=S_{yx}(f)$ , so the full contribution to the cross power is, generally, from twice the real part of either individual **CPSD**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In light of this, the PSD is seen to be a special case of the CSD for $x(t)=y(t)$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] If $x(t)$ and $y(t)$ are real signals (e.g. voltage or current), their Fourier transforms ${\hat {x}}(f)$ and ${\hat {y}}(f)$ are usually restricted to positive frequencies by convention.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The goal of spectral density estimation is to estimate the spectral density of a random signal from a sequence of time samples.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Depending on what is known about the signal, estimation techniques can involve parametric or non-parametric approaches, and may be based on time-domain or frequency-domain analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] For example, a common parametric technique involves fitting the observations to an autoregressive model.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] A common non-parametric technique is the periodogram.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The spectral density is usually estimated using Fourier transform methods (such as the Welch method), but other techniques such as the maximum entropy method can also be used.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In 2026, the unbiased estimation of spectral densities and their higher-order generalisations has been established in the context of polyspectra based on windowed Fourier-transforms and K-statistic.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Any signal that can be represented as a variable that varies in time has a corresponding frequency spectrum.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] This includes familiar entities such as visible light (perceived as color), musical notes (perceived as pitch), radio/TV (specified by their frequency, or sometimes wavelength) and even the regular rotation of the earth.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] When these signals are viewed in the form of a frequency spectrum, certain aspects of the received signals or the underlying processes producing them are revealed.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] In some cases the frequency spectrum may include a distinct peak corresponding to a sine wave component.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] And additionally there may be peaks corresponding to harmonics of a fundamental peak, indicating a periodic signal which is *not* simply sinusoidal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Or a continuous spectrum may show narrow frequency intervals which are strongly enhanced corresponding to resonances, or frequency intervals containing almost zero power as would be produced by a notch filter.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The concept and use of the power spectrum of a signal is fundamental in electrical engineering, especially in electronic communication systems, including radio communications, radars, and related systems, plus passive remote sensing technology.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Electronic instruments called spectrum analyzers are used to observe and measure the ***power spectra*** of signals.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] The spectrum analyzer measures the magnitude of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) of an input signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] If the signal being analyzed can be considered a stationary process, the STFT is a good smoothed estimate of its power spectral density.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/cross-spectral-density] Primordial fluctuations, density variations in the early universe, are quantified by a power spectrum which gives the power of the variations as a function of spatial scale.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In mathematics, the **discrete-time Fourier transform** (**DTFT**) is a form of Fourier analysis that is applicable to a sequence of discrete values.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The DTFT is often used to analyze samples of a continuous function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The term *discrete-time* refers to the fact that the transform operates on discrete data, often samples whose interval has units of time.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] From uniformly spaced samples it produces a function of frequency that is a periodic summation of the continuous Fourier transform of the original continuous function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In simpler terms, when you take the DTFT of regularly-spaced samples of a continuous signal, you get repeating (and possibly overlapping) copies of the signal's frequency spectrum, spaced at intervals corresponding to the sampling frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Under certain theoretical conditions, described by the sampling theorem, the original continuous function can be recovered perfectly from the DTFT and thus from the original discrete samples.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The DTFT itself is a continuous function of frequency, but discrete samples of it can be readily calculated via the discrete Fourier transform (DFT) (see § Sampling the DTFT), which is by far the most common method of modern Fourier analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The inverse DTFT reconstructs the original sampled data sequence, while the inverse DFT produces a periodic summation of the original sequence.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The fast Fourier transform (FFT) is an algorithm for computing one cycle of the DFT, and its inverse produces one cycle of the inverse DFT.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Let $s(t)$ be a continuous function in the time domain.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] We can reduce the integral into a summation by sampling $s(t)$ at intervals of T seconds (see Fourier transform § Numerical integration of a series of ordered pairs).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Specifically, we can replace $s(t)$ with a discrete sequence of its samples, $s(nT)$ , for integer values of n , and replace the differential element $dt$ with the sampling period T .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] This Fourier series (in frequency) is a continuous periodic function, whose periodicity is the sampling frequency $1/T$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The subscript $1/T$ distinguishes it from the continuous Fourier transform $S(f)$ , and from the angular frequency form of the DTFT.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The components of the periodic summation are centered at integer values (denoted by k ) of a normalized frequency (cycles per sample).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Ordinary/physical frequency (cycles per second) is the product of k and the sample-rate, $f_{s}=1/T.$ For sufficiently large $f_{s},$ the $k=0$ term can be observed in the region $[-f_{s}/2,f_{s}/2]$ with little or no distortion (aliasing) from the other terms.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] **Fig.1** depicts an example where $1/T$ is not large enough to prevent aliasing.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The modulated Dirac comb function is a mathematical abstraction sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An operation that recovers the discrete data sequence from the DTFT function is called an *inverse DTFT*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The $s_{_{N}}$ sequence is the inverse DFT.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Thus, our sampling of the DTFT causes the inverse transform to become periodic.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The array of $|S_{k}|^{2}$ values is known as a *periodogram*, and the parameter N is called NFFT in the Matlab function of the same name.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In order to evaluate one cycle of $s_{_{N}}$ numerically, we require a finite-length $s[n]$ sequence.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] For instance, a long sequence might be truncated by a window function of length L resulting in three cases worthy of special mention.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] For notational simplicity, consider the $s[n]$ values below to represent the values modified by the window function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Recall that decimation of sampled data in one domain (time or frequency) produces overlap (sometimes known as aliasing) in the other, and vice versa.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Compared to an L -length DFT, the $s_{_{N}}$ summation/overlap causes decimation in frequency, leaving only DTFT samples least affected by spectral leakage.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] That is usually a priority when implementing an FFT filter-bank (channelizer).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] With a conventional window function of length $L,$ scalloping loss would be unacceptable.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] So multi-block windows are created using FIR filter design tools.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Their frequency profile is flat at the highest point and falls off quickly at the midpoint between the remaining DTFT samples.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The larger the value of parameter $I,$ the better the potential performance.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] When a symmetric, L -length window function ( s ) is truncated by 1 coefficient it is called *periodic* or *DFT-even*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] That is a common practice, but the truncation affects the DTFT (spectral leakage) by a small amount.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] It is at least of academic interest to characterize that effect.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An N -length DFT of the truncated window produces frequency samples at intervals of $1/N,$ instead of $1/L.$ The samples are real-valued, but their values do not exactly match the DTFT of the symmetric window.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The periodic summation, $s_{_{N}},$ along with an N -length DFT, can also be used to sample the DTFT at intervals of $1/N.$ Those samples are also real-valued and do exactly match the DTFT (example: File:Sampling the Discrete-time Fourier transform.svg).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] To use the full symmetric window for spectral analysis at the $1/N$ spacing, one would combine the $n=0$ and $n=N$ data samples (by addition, because the symmetrical window weights them equally) and then apply the truncated symmetric window and the N -length DFT.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] In order to take advantage of a fast Fourier transform algorithm for computing the DFT, the summation is usually performed over all N terms, even though $N-L$ of them are zeros.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Therefore, the case $L<N$ is often referred to as **zero-padding**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Spectral leakage, which increases as L decreases, is detrimental to certain important performance metrics, such as resolution of multiple frequency components and the amount of noise measured by each DTFT sample.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] But those things don't always matter, for instance when the $s[n]$ sequence is a noiseless sinusoid (or a constant), shaped by a window function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Then it is a common practice to use *zero-padding* to graphically display and compare the detailed leakage patterns of window functions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] An important special case is the circular convolution of sequences s and y defined by $s_{_{N}}*y,$ where $s_{_{N}}$ is a periodic summation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The significance of this result is explained at circular convolution and fast convolution algorithms.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] $S_{2\pi }(\omega )$ is a Fourier series that can also be expressed in terms of the bilateral Z-transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] where the $S_{z}$ notation distinguishes the Z-transform from the Fourier transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Note that when parameter T changes, the terms of $S_{2\pi }(\omega )$ remain a constant separation $2\pi$ apart, and their width scales up or down.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] The terms of *S*1/*T*(*f*) remain a constant width and their separation 1/*T* scales up or down.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] Some common transform pairs are shown in the table below.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/discrete-time-fourier-transform] This table shows some mathematical operations in the time domain and the corresponding effects in the frequency domain.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis grew from the study of Fourier series, and is named after Joseph Fourier, who showed that representing a function as a sum of trigonometric functions greatly simplifies the study of heat transfer.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis has applications in many areas of pure and applied mathematics, in the sciences and in engineering.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The process of decomposing a function into oscillatory components is often called Fourier analysis, while the operation of rebuilding the function from these pieces is known as **Fourier synthesis**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] For example, determining what component frequencies are present in a musical note would involve computing the Fourier transform of a sampled musical note.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] One can then re-synthesize the same sound by mixing purely harmonic sounds with frequency components as revealed in the Fourier analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In mathematics, the term *Fourier analysis* often refers to the study of both operations.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The decomposition process itself is called a Fourier transformation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Its output, the Fourier transform, is often given a more specific name, which depends on the domain and other properties of the function being transformed.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Moreover, the original concept of Fourier analysis has been extended over time to apply to more and more abstract and general situations as group representation theory, and the general field is often known as harmonic analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Each transform used for analysis (see list of Fourier-related transforms) has a corresponding inverse transform that can be used for synthesis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In applications, Fourier analysis is usually applied to a "signal" depending on "time" sampled at equal time intervals of length T .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The Fourier transform converts this sequence in an equally long sequence of amplitudes for sines and cosines (or more conveniently, complex exponentials) with frequency multiples of $1/T$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] This is particularly useful to detect strong periodic components in the signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The fast Fourier transform is an efficient algorithm to compute these amplitudes.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Different approaches have been developed for analyzing unequally spaced data, notably the least-squares spectral analysis (LSSA) methods that use a least squares fit of sinusoids to data samples, similar to Fourier analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Fourier analysis, the most used spectral method in science, generally boosts long-periodic noise in long gapped records; LSSA mitigates such problems.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In forensics, laboratory infrared spectrophotometers use Fourier transform analysis for measuring the wavelengths of light at which a material will absorb in the infrared spectrum.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The FT method is used to decode the measured signals and record the wavelength data.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] And by using a computer, these Fourier calculations are rapidly carried out, so that in a matter of seconds, a computer-operated FT-IR instrument can produce an infrared absorption pattern comparable to that of a prism instrument.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Fourier transformation is also useful as a compact representation of a signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] For example, JPEG compression uses a variant of the Fourier transformation (discrete cosine transform) of small square pieces of a digital image.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The Fourier components of each square are rounded to lower arithmetic precision, and weak components are eliminated, so that the remaining components can be stored very compactly.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In image reconstruction, each image square is reassembled from the preserved approximate Fourier-transformed components, which are then inverse-transformed to produce an approximation of the original image.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In signal processing, the Fourier transform often takes a time series or a function of continuous time, and maps it into a frequency spectrum.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] When a function $s(t)$ is a function of time and represents a physical signal, the transform has a standard interpretation as the frequency spectrum of the signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The magnitude of the resulting complex-valued function $S(f)$ at frequency f represents the amplitude of a frequency component whose initial phase is given by the angle of $S(f)$ (polar coordinates).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Fourier transforms are not limited to functions of time, and temporal frequencies.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] They can equally be applied to analyze *spatial* frequencies, and indeed for nearly any function domain.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] This justifies their use in such diverse branches as image processing, heat conduction, and automatic control.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] When processing signals, such as audio, radio waves, light waves, seismic waves, and even images, Fourier analysis can isolate narrowband components of a compound waveform, concentrating them for easier detection or removal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] A large family of signal processing techniques consist of Fourier-transforming a signal, manipulating the Fourier-transformed data in a simple way, and reversing the transformation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The fifth variant, the DFT, is used only in the case where the input function is discrete in its domain and limited to a finite region of support.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The DFT is the only variant that can be calculated numerically, and it can be used to approximate the other four variants.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Most often, the unqualified term **Fourier transform** refers to the transform of functions of a continuous real argument, and it produces a continuous function of frequency, known as a *frequency distribution* or *spectrum*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] One function is transformed into another, and the operation is reversible.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Evaluating this quantity for all values of f produces the *frequency-domain* function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Note that any $s(t)$ whose transform has the same discrete sample values can be used in the periodic summation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] A sufficient condition for recovering $s(t)$ (and therefore $S(f)$ ) from just these samples (i.e. from the Fourier series) is that the non-zero portion of $s(t)$ be confined to a known interval of duration $P,$ which is the frequency domain dual of the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] See Fourier series for more information, including the historical development.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The DTFT is the mathematical dual of the time-domain Fourier series.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Thus the **DTFT** of the $s[n]$ sequence is also the **Fourier transform** of the modulated Dirac comb function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Parameter T corresponds to the sampling interval, and this Fourier series can now be recognized as a form of the Poisson summation formula.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] But under certain idealized conditions one can theoretically recover $S(f)$ and $s(t)$ exactly.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] This is a cornerstone in the foundation of digital signal processing.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Another reason to be interested in $S_{\tfrac {1}{T}}(f)$ is that it often provides insight into the amount of aliasing caused by the sampling process.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Applications of the DTFT are not limited to sampled functions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The $S[k]$ sequence is customarily known as the **DFT** of one cycle of $s_{_{N}}.$ It is also N -periodic, so it is never necessary to compute more than N coefficients.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Conversely, when one wants to compute an arbitrary number $(N)$ of discrete samples of one cycle of a continuous DTFT, $S_{\tfrac {1}{T}}(f),$ it can be done by computing the relatively simple DFT of $s_{_{N}}[n],$ as defined above.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] (see Discrete-time Fourier transform § L=N×I) In most cases of practical interest, the $s[n]$ sequence represents a longer sequence that was truncated by the application of a finite-length window function or FIR filter array.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The DFT can be computed using a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm, which makes it a practical and important transformation on computers.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] For periodic functions, both the Fourier transform and the DTFT comprise only a discrete set of frequency components (Fourier series), and the transforms diverge at those frequencies.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] One common practice (not discussed above) is to handle that divergence via Dirac delta and Dirac comb functions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] But the same spectral information can be discerned from just one cycle of the periodic function, since all the other cycles are identical.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Similarly, finite-duration functions can be represented as a Fourier series, with no actual loss of information except that the periodicity of the inverse transform is a mere artifact.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] It is common in practice for the duration of *s*(•) to be limited to the period, P or N.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] But these formulas do not require that condition.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] When the real and imaginary parts of a complex function are decomposed into their even and odd parts, there are four components, denoted below by the subscripts RE, RO, IE, and IO.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] An early form of harmonic series dates back to ancient Babylonian mathematics, where they were used to compute ephemerides (tables of astronomical positions).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The Classical Greek concepts of deferent and epicycle in the Ptolemaic system of astronomy were related to Fourier series (see Deferent and epicycle § Mathematical formalism).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In modern times, variants of the discrete Fourier transform were used by Alexis Clairaut in 1754 to compute an orbit, which has been described as the first formula for the DFT, and in 1759 by Joseph Louis Lagrange, in computing the coefficients of a trigonometric series for a vibrating string.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Technically, Clairaut's work was a cosine-only series (a form of discrete cosine transform), while Lagrange's work was a sine-only series (a form of discrete sine transform); a true cosine+sine DFT was used by Gauss in 1805 for trigonometric interpolation of asteroid orbits.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Euler and Lagrange both discretized the vibrating string problem, using what would today be called samples.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] where ζ is a cubic root of unity, which is the DFT of order 3.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] Independently of Fourier, astronomer Friedrich Wilhelm Bessel also introduced Fourier series to solve Kepler's equation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] His work was published in 1819, unaware of Fourier's work which remained unpublished until 1822.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The subsequent development of the field is known as harmonic analysis, and is also an early instance of representation theory.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The first fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm for the DFT was discovered around 1805 by Carl Friedrich Gauss when interpolating measurements of the orbit of the asteroids Juno and Pallas, although that particular FFT algorithm is more often attributed to its modern rediscoverers Cooley and Tukey.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] In signal processing terms, a function (of time) is a representation of a signal with perfect *time resolution*, but no frequency information, while the Fourier transform has perfect *frequency resolution*, but no time information.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] As alternatives to the Fourier transform, in time–frequency analysis, one uses time–frequency transforms to represent signals in a form that has some time information and some frequency information – by the uncertainty principle, there is a trade-off between these.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] The Fourier variants can also be generalized to Fourier transforms on arbitrary locally compact Abelian topological groups, which are studied in harmonic analysis; there, the Fourier transform takes functions on a group to functions on the dual group.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] This treatment also allows a general formulation of the convolution theorem, which relates Fourier transforms and convolutions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] See also the Pontryagin duality for the generalized underpinnings of the Fourier transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/fourier-analysis] More specific, Fourier analysis can be done on cosets, even discrete cosets.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] In signal processing, a **periodogram** is an estimate of the spectral density of a signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] The term was coined by Arthur Schuster in 1898.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] Today, the periodogram is a component of more sophisticated methods (see spectral estimation).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] It is the most common tool for examining the amplitude vs frequency characteristics of FIR filters and window functions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] FFT spectrum analyzers are also implemented as a time-sequence of periodograms.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] There are at least two different definitions in use today.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] One of them involves time-averaging, and one does not.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] Time-averaging is also the purview of other articles (Bartlett's method and Welch's method).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] This article is not about time-averaging.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] which is precisely determined by the samples *x*(*nT*) that span the non-zero duration of *x*(*t*) (see Discrete-time Fourier transform).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] When a periodogram is used to examine the detailed characteristics of an FIR filter or window function, the parameter N is chosen to be several multiples of the non-zero duration of the *x*[*n*] sequence, which is called *zero-padding* (see § Sampling the DTFT).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] When it is used to implement a filter bank, N is several sub-multiples of the non-zero duration of the *x*[*n*] sequence (see § Sampling the DTFT).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] One of the periodogram's deficiencies is that the variance at a given frequency does not decrease as the number of samples used in the computation increases.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] It does not provide the averaging needed to analyze noiselike signals or even sinusoids at low signal-to-noise ratios.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] Window functions and filter impulse responses are noiseless, but many other signals require more sophisticated methods of spectral estimation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] Periodogram-based techniques introduce small biases that are unacceptable in some applications.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/periodogram] Other techniques that do not rely on periodograms are presented in the spectral density estimation article.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A **wavelet** is a wave-like oscillation with an amplitude that begins at zero, increases or decreases, and then returns to zero one or more times.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelets are termed a "brief oscillation".
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A taxonomy of wavelets has been established, based on the number and direction of its pulses.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelets are imbued with specific properties that make them useful for signal processing.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For example, a wavelet could be created to have a frequency of middle C and a short duration of roughly one tenth of a second.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] If this wavelet were to be convolved with a signal created from the recording of a melody, then the resulting signal would be useful for determining when the middle C note appeared in the song.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Mathematically, a wavelet correlates with a signal if a portion of the signal is similar.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Correlation is at the core of many practical wavelet applications.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] As a mathematical tool, wavelets can be used to extract information from many kinds of data, including audio signals and images.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Sets of wavelets are needed to analyze data fully.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] "Complementary" wavelets decompose a signal without gaps or overlaps so that the decomposition process is mathematically reversible.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Thus, sets of complementary wavelets are useful in wavelet-based compression/decompression algorithms, where it is desirable to recover the original information with minimal loss.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In formal terms, this representation is a wavelet series representation of a square-integrable function with respect to either a complete, orthonormal set of basis functions, or an overcomplete set or frame of a vector space, for the Hilbert space of square-integrable functions.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This is accomplished through coherent states.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In classical physics, the diffraction phenomenon is described by the Huygens–Fresnel principle that treats each point in a propagating wavefront as a collection of individual spherical wavelets.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The characteristic bending pattern is most pronounced when a wave from a coherent source (such as a laser) encounters a slit/aperture that is comparable in size to its wavelength.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This is due to the addition, or interference, of different points on the wavefront (or, equivalently, each wavelet) that travel by paths of different lengths to the registering surface.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Multiple, closely spaced openings (e.g., a diffraction grating), can result in a complex pattern of varying intensity.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The word *wavelet* has been used for decades in digital signal processing and exploration geophysics.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The equivalent French word *ondelette* meaning "small wave" was used by Jean Morlet and Alex Grossmann in the early 1980s.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet theory is applicable to several subjects.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] All wavelet transforms may be considered forms of time-frequency representation for continuous-time (analog) signals and so are related to harmonic analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Discrete wavelet transform (continuous in time) of a discrete-time (sampled) signal by using discrete-time filterbanks of dyadic (octave band) configuration is a wavelet approximation to that signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The coefficients of such a filter bank are called the shift and scaling coefficients in wavelets nomenclature.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] These filterbanks may contain either finite impulse response (FIR) or infinite impulse response (IIR) filters.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The wavelets forming a continuous wavelet transform (CWT) are subject to the uncertainty principle of Fourier analysis respective sampling theory: given a signal with some event in it, one cannot assign simultaneously an exact time and frequency response scale to that event.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The product of the uncertainties of time and frequency response scale has a lower bound.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Thus, in the scaleogram of a continuous wavelet transform of this signal, such an event marks an entire region in the time-scale plane, instead of just one point.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Also, discrete wavelet bases may be considered in the context of other forms of the uncertainty principle.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are broadly divided into three classes: continuous, discrete and multiresolution-based.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In continuous wavelet transforms, a given signal of finite energy is projected on a continuous family of frequency bands (or similar subspaces of the *Lp* function space *L*2(**R**) ).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For instance the signal may be represented on every frequency band of the form [*f*, 2*f*] for all positive frequencies *f* > 0.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Then, the original signal can be reconstructed by a suitable integration over all the resulting frequency components.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The frequency bands or subspaces (sub-bands) are scaled versions of a subspace at scale 1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This subspace in turn is in most situations generated by the shifts of one generating function ψ in *L*2(**R**), the *mother wavelet*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For the example of the scale one frequency band [1, 2] this function is $\psi (t)=2\,\operatorname {sinc} (2t)-\,\operatorname {sinc} (t)={\frac {\sin(2\pi t)-\sin(\pi t)}{\pi t}}$ with the (normalized) sinc function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The subspace of scale *a* or frequency band [1/*a*, 2/*a*] is generated by the functions (sometimes called *child wavelets*) $\psi _{a,b}(t)={\frac {1}{\sqrt {a}}}\psi \left({\frac {t-b}{a}}\right),$ where *a* is positive and defines the scale and *b* is any real number and defines the shift.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The pair (*a*, *b*) defines a point in the right halfplane **R**+ × **R**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For the analysis of the signal *x*, one can assemble the wavelet coefficients into a scaleogram of the signal.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] It is computationally impossible to analyze a signal using all wavelet coefficients, so one may wonder if it is sufficient to pick a discrete subset of the upper halfplane to be able to reconstruct a signal from the corresponding wavelet coefficients.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] One such system is the affine system for some real parameters *a* > 1, *b* > 0.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The corresponding discrete subset of the halfplane consists of all the points (*am*, *nb am*) with *m*, *n* in **Z**.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In any discretised wavelet transform, there are only a finite number of wavelet coefficients for each bounded rectangular region in the upper halfplane.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Still, each coefficient requires the evaluation of an integral.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In special situations this numerical complexity can be avoided if the scaled and shifted wavelets form a multiresolution analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This means that there has to exist an auxiliary function, the *father wavelet* φ in *L*2(**R**), and that *a* is an integer.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A typical choice is *a* = 2 and *b* = 1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The most famous pair of father and mother wavelets is the Daubechies 4-tap wavelet.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Note that not every orthonormal discrete wavelet basis can be associated to a multiresolution analysis; for example, the Journe wavelet admits no multiresolution analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In analogy to the sampling theorem one may conclude that the space *Vm* with sampling distance 2*m* more or less covers the frequency baseband from 0 to 1/2*m*-1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] As orthogonal complement, *Wm* roughly covers the band [1/2*m*−1, 1/2*m*].
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Both pairs of identities form the basis for the algorithm of the fast wavelet transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For processing temporal signals in real time, it is essential that the wavelet filters do not access signal values from the future as well as that minimal temporal latencies can be obtained.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Time-causal wavelets representations have been developed by Szu et al and Lindeberg, with the latter method also involving a memory-efficient time-recursive implementation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For practical applications, and for efficiency reasons, one prefers continuously differentiable functions with compact support as mother (prototype) wavelet (functions).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Being in this space ensures that one can formulate the conditions of zero mean and square norm one: $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }\psi (t)\,dt=0$ is the condition for zero mean, and $\int _{-\infty }^{\infty }|\psi (t)|^{2}\,dt=1$ is the condition for square norm one.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For *ψ* to be a wavelet for the continuous wavelet transform (see there for exact statement), the mother wavelet must satisfy an admissibility criterion (loosely speaking, a kind of half-differentiability) in order to get a stably invertible transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For the discrete wavelet transform, one needs at least the condition that the wavelet series is a representation of the identity in the space *L*2(**R**).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Most constructions of discrete WT make use of the multiresolution analysis, which defines the wavelet by a scaling function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This scaling function itself is a solution to a functional equation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For the continuous WT, the pair (*a*,*b*) varies over the full half-plane **R**+ × **R**; for the discrete WT this pair varies over a discrete subset of it, which is also called *affine group*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] These functions are often incorrectly referred to as the basis functions of the (continuous) transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In fact, as in the continuous Fourier transform, there is no basis in the continuous wavelet transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Time-frequency interpretation uses a subtly different formulation (after Delprat).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The wavelet transform is often compared with the Fourier transform, in which signals are represented as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In fact, the Fourier transform can be viewed as a special case of the continuous wavelet transform with the choice of the mother wavelet $\psi (t)=e^{-2\pi it}$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The main difference in general is that wavelets are localized in both time and frequency whereas the standard Fourier transform is only localized in frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is similar to the wavelet transform, in that it is also time and frequency localized, but there are issues with the frequency/time resolution trade-off.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Multiplication with a rectangular window in the time domain corresponds to convolution with a $\operatorname {sinc} (\Delta _{t}\omega )$ function in the frequency domain, resulting in spurious ringing artifacts for short/localized temporal windows.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] With the continuous-time Fourier transform, $\Delta _{t}\to \infty$ and this convolution is with a delta function in Fourier space, resulting in the true Fourier transform of the signal $x(t)$ .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The window function may be some other apodizing filter, such as a Gaussian.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The choice of windowing function will affect the approximation error relative to the true Fourier transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A given resolution cell's time-bandwidth product may not be exceeded with the STFT.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] All STFT basis elements maintain a uniform spectral and temporal support for all temporal shifts or offsets, thereby attaining an equal resolution in time for lower and higher frequencies.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The resolution is purely determined by the sampling width.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In contrast, the wavelet transform's multiresolutional properties enables large temporal supports for lower frequencies while maintaining short temporal widths for higher frequencies by the scaling properties of the wavelet transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This property extends conventional time-frequency analysis into time-scale analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The discrete wavelet transform is less computationally complex, taking O(*N*) time as compared to O(*N* log *N*) for the fast Fourier transform (FFT).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This computational advantage is not inherent to the transform, but reflects the choice of a logarithmic division of frequency, in contrast to the equally spaced frequency divisions of the FFT which uses the same basis functions as the discrete Fourier transform (DFT).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This complexity only applies when the filter size has no relation to the signal size.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A wavelet without compact support such as the Shannon wavelet would require O(*N*2).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] An orthogonal wavelet is entirely defined by the scaling filter – a low-pass finite impulse response (FIR) filter of length 2*N* and sum 1.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In biorthogonal wavelets, separate decomposition and reconstruction filters are defined.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For analysis with orthogonal wavelets the high pass filter is calculated as the quadrature mirror filter of the low pass, and reconstruction filters are the time reverse of the decomposition filters.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Daubechies and Symlet wavelets can be defined by the scaling filter.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelets are defined by the wavelet function ψ(*t*) (i.e. the mother wavelet) and scaling function φ(*t*) (also called father wavelet) in the time domain.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The wavelet function is in effect a band-pass filter and scaling that for each level halves its bandwidth.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This creates the problem that in order to cover the entire spectrum, an infinite number of levels would be required.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The scaling function filters the lowest level of the transform and ensures all the spectrum is covered.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For a wavelet with compact support, φ(*t*) can be considered finite in length and is equivalent to the scaling filter *g*.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The wavelet only has a time domain representation as the wavelet function ψ(*t*).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For instance, Mexican hat wavelets can be defined by a wavelet function.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] See a list of a few continuous wavelets.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The development of wavelets can be linked to several separate trains of thought, starting with Alfréd Haar's work in the early 20th century.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Later work by Dennis Gabor yielded Gabor atoms (1946), which are constructed similarly to wavelets, and applied to similar purposes.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The JPEG 2000 standard was developed from 1997 to 2000 by a Joint Photographic Experts Group (JPEG) committee chaired by Touradj Ebrahimi (later the JPEG president).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In contrast to the DCT algorithm used by the original JPEG format, JPEG 2000 instead uses discrete wavelet transform (DWT) algorithms.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] It uses the CDF 9/7 wavelet transform (developed by Ingrid Daubechies in 1992) for its lossy compression algorithm, and the Le Gall–Tabatabai (LGT) 5/3 discrete-time filter bank (developed by Didier Le Gall and Ali J.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Tabatabai in 1988) for its lossless compression algorithm.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] JPEG 2000 technology, which includes the Motion JPEG 2000 extension, was selected as the video coding standard for digital cinema in 2004.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A wavelet is a mathematical function used to divide a given function or continuous-time signal into different scale components.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Usually one can assign a frequency range to each scale component.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Each scale component can then be studied with a resolution that matches its scale.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A wavelet transform is the representation of a function by wavelets.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The wavelets are scaled and translated copies (known as "daughter wavelets") of a finite-length or fast-decaying oscillating waveform (known as the "mother wavelet").
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet transforms have advantages over traditional Fourier transforms for representing functions that have discontinuities and sharp peaks, and for accurately deconstructing and reconstructing finite, non-periodic and/or non-stationary signals.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are classified into discrete wavelet transforms (DWTs) and continuous wavelet transforms (CWTs).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Note that both DWT and CWT are continuous-time (analog) transforms.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] They can be used to represent continuous-time (analog) signals.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] CWTs operate over every possible scale and translation whereas DWTs use a specific subset of scale and translation values or representation grid.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] There are a large number of wavelet transforms each suitable for different applications.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] There are a number of generalized transforms of which the wavelet transform is a special case.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For example, Yosef Joseph Segman introduced scale into the Heisenberg group, giving rise to a continuous transform space that is a function of time, scale, and frequency.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] The CWT is a two-dimensional slice through the resulting 3d time-scale-frequency volume.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Another example of a generalized transform is the chirplet transform in which the CWT is also a two dimensional slice through the chirplet transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] An important application area for generalized transforms involves systems in which high frequency resolution is crucial.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For example, darkfield electron optical transforms intermediate between direct and reciprocal space have been widely used in the harmonic analysis of atom clustering, i.e. in the study of crystals and crystal defects.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Fractional wavelet transform (FRWT) is a generalization of the classical wavelet transform in the fractional Fourier transform domains.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This transform is capable of providing the time- and fractional-domain information simultaneously and representing signals in the time-fractional-frequency plane.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Generally, an approximation to DWT is used for data compression if a signal is already sampled, and the CWT for signal analysis.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Thus, DWT approximation is commonly used in engineering and computer science, and the CWT in scientific research.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Like some other transforms, wavelet transforms can be used to transform data, then encode the transformed data, resulting in effective compression.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] For example, JPEG 2000 is an image compression standard that uses biorthogonal wavelets.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This means that although the frame is overcomplete, it is a *tight frame* (see types of frames of a vector space), and the same frame functions (except for conjugation in the case of complex wavelets) are used for both analysis and synthesis, i.e., in both the forward and inverse transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] A related use is for smoothing/denoising data based on wavelet coefficient thresholding, also called wavelet shrinkage.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] By adaptively thresholding the wavelet coefficients that correspond to undesired frequency components smoothing and/or denoising operations can be performed.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet transforms are also starting to be used for communication applications.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM is the basic modulation scheme used in HD-PLC (a power line communications technology developed by Panasonic), and in one of the optional modes included in the IEEE 1901 standard.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelet OFDM can achieve deeper notches than traditional FFT OFDM, and wavelet OFDM does not require a guard interval (which usually represents significant overhead in FFT OFDM systems).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Often, signals can be represented well as a sum of sinusoids.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] However, consider a non-continuous signal with an abrupt discontinuity; this signal can still be represented as a sum of sinusoids, but requires an infinite number, which is an observation known as Gibbs phenomenon.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This, then, requires an infinite number of Fourier coefficients, which is not practical for many applications, such as compression.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Wavelets are more useful for describing these signals with discontinuities because of their time-localized behavior (both Fourier and wavelet transforms are frequency-localized, but wavelets have an additional time-localization property).
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Because of this, many types of signals in practice may be non-sparse in the Fourier domain, but very sparse in the wavelet domain.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This is particularly useful in signal reconstruction, especially in the recently popular field of compressed sensing.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] (Note that the short-time Fourier transform (STFT) is also localized in time and frequency, but there are often problems with the frequency-time resolution trade-off.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] This motivates why wavelet transforms are now being adopted for a vast number of applications, often replacing the conventional Fourier transform.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Many areas of physics have seen this paradigm shift, including molecular dynamics, chaos theory, ab initio calculations, astrophysics, gravitational wave transient data analysis, density-matrix localisation, seismology, optics, turbulence and quantum mechanics.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] In computer vision and image processing, the notion of scale space representation and Gaussian derivative operators is regarded as a canonical multi-scale representation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Suppose we measure a noisy signal $x=s+v$ , where s represents the signal and v represents the noise.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Let the wavelet transform of x be $y=W^{T}x=W^{T}s+W^{T}v=p+z$ , where $p=W^{T}s$ is the wavelet transform of the signal component and $z=W^{T}v$ is the wavelet transform of the noise component.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Since W is orthogonal, the estimation problem amounts to recovery of a signal in iid Gaussian noise.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] As p is sparse, one method is to apply a Gaussian mixture model for p .
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] By setting coefficients that fall below a shrinkage threshold to zero, once the inverse transform is applied, an expectedly small amount of signal is lost due to the sparsity assumption.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Typically, the above-threshold coefficients are not modified during this process.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Some algorithms for wavelet-based denoising may attenuate larger coefficients as well, based on a statistical estimate of the amount of noise expected to be removed by such an attenuation.
[src:spectral-analysis-stats/wavelet] Agarwal et al. proposed wavelet based advanced linear and nonlinear methods to construct and investigate Climate as complex networks at different timescales.
